INFO 2025-05-08 02:39:42,254 documents 1414 140302029010624 Chunks: ['#### Republic of the Philippines MINDANAO STATE UNIVERSITY Marawi City\n\n## OFFICE OF THE SECRETARY OF THE UNIVERSITY AND OF THE BOARD OF REGENTS\n\nEXCERPTS FROM THE MINUTES OF THE 262ND MEETING OF THE BOARD OF REGENTS HELD ON MARCH 6, 2023 VIA ZOOM TELECONFERENCING AND FACE-TO-FACE AT CHED CONFERENCE ROOM, HEDC BUILDING, C.P. GARCIA AVENUE, DILIMAN, QUEZON CITY\n\nX-X-X\n\nX-X-X\n\nX-X-X\n\n# "RESOLUTION NO. 32, S. 2023"\n\nRESOLVED, that upon the recommendation "the Prosident of the Mindanao State University and the Executive Committee of the Board of Regents, the Splitting of the existing OEE into three (3) Distinct Departments, namely: Dept. of F ectrical En neering, Dept. of Electronics Engineering, Dept. of mpute Engineering and Mechatronics, with pertinent docume. attacned as Annex "\\/" (under separate cover), and made intr ral oarts this resolution, is hereby APPROVED.\n\nX-X-X\n\nX-X-X\n\n## APPROVED"\n\nX-X-X\n\nCERTIFIED TRUE AND CORRECT:\n\nD', 'X-X-X\n\nX-X-X\n\n## APPROVED"\n\nX-X-X\n\nCERTIFIED TRUE AND CORRECT:\n\nD\n\nATTY. SHIDIKT. ABANKAS, MDM Secretary of the University and of the Board of Regents\n\nSTA:rlf 15 March 2023 (Not valid without seal) OFFICE OF THE VICE-CHANCELLOR FOR ACADEMIC AFFAIRS\n\nMINDANAO STATE UNIVERSITY - ILIGAN INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY\n\n2023005103\n\nwww.msuiit.edu.ph\n\nFebruary 9, 2023\n\n#### ALIZEDNEY M. DITUCALAN BRIEF FOR : Chancellor\n\nSUBJECT : Splitting of the Existing Department of Elec. cal Engineering and Technology of th of Engineering into Three (3) Distinct Departments\n\nAs favourably acted upon by the Academ Plan. Jommittee in its meeting held on January 31, 2023, we are endorsing to your offic the attached proposal for the Splitting of the Existing Department of Ele trical Engineering and Technology of the College of Engineering into Three (3) Fistin Der rtments, for submission to the Board of Regents\' next meeting.\n\n> ARIME B. METILLO, Ph.D. ce Chancellor for Academic Affairs, and CPC Chairperson', '> ARIME B. METILLO, Ph.D. ce Chancellor for Academic Affairs, and CPC Chairperson\n\nInfluencing the Future\n\n# EXCERPTS MINUTES OF THE APC MEETING\n\nJanuary 31, 2023 Case Room, CASS Bldg.\n\n### ATTENDANCE\n\nAtty. Alizedney M. Ditucalan, Chancellor Prof. Ephrime B. Metillo, VCAA, Presiding Officer Atty. Yaslani Bantuas, VCAF Prof. Pamela F. Resurreccion, VCPD Prof. Rohane M. Derogongan, VCSS Prof. Joey Genevieve Matinez, VCIA Prof. Marie Joy D. Banawa, CASS Dean Prof. Monera Salic-Hairulla, CED Dean Prof. Ma. Sheila K. RAmos, COET Dean Prof. Maria Rizalia Y. Teves, CEBA Dean Prof. Jan Mickelle Maratas, CSM Dean Prof. Rabby Q. Lavilles, CCS Dean and UASP Prof. Mylene M. Uy, PRISM Director Prof. Jun Karren V. Caparoso, CAELL Director Prof. Irish Mae F. Dalona, CGEM Director Prof. Cenie V. Malabanan, CPI Director Prof. Liza B. Pama-ong, IDS Asst. Principal Prof. Rosario L. Reserva, CAPP Chairperson Prof. Edgar Allan Donasco, FU President', "Mr. Rex Ortega, Campus Secretary Mr. Ricardo Enguito, Registrar Asst. Prof. Phyllis Marie Teanco, OSDS Prof. Mark Anthony Torres, CIS Director Jhune Ace A. Lubang, Representing KASAMA Ms. Mercedita G. Resente, OVCAA, Recording Asst. Prof. Josephin May Grace Famoso , Recording Others Present: Prof. Juvanni 6 & AERC Director Rohanima Guro, IF C St f Shirly Gr Selo, OC. Staff Prof. Penni Micu Jo, DEET Chairperson Ass' . Prof. Abu . asheed T. Tanggol, CLGS Directo Dir melyn R Mordeno, HRMD Sst. nnah Pierre Talle, CASS Faculty Prof. Marjorie Joy Magdadaro, CASS FAculty\n\n#### AGENDA:\n\n. PRELIMINARY 11.\n\nNEW BUSINESS\n\n1. 2.\n\n3 A Of remin\n\nSplitting the DEET into 3 Distinct Departments", '| 3.F. Splitting of the DEE7 mo 3 chect Departments                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                |                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           |', '|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|', '| The proposal was presented hy r. Rennie E. Miculob, DEET Chairperson.<br>The proposal was ora auuress the issues that the department is facing<br>with the current set<br>Contained in attache copy of the proposal are details of the following:<br>Background ther posal<br>Rationale<br>- Advantages of splitting the department<br>- The proposed creation of the 3 departments with the corresponding<br>programs under each - after the splitting<br>The proposed organizational structure and its description<br>The faculty loading and staff/laboratory technicians hiring requirements | Recommended for<br>approval.<br>Prof. Cenie Malabanan,<br>CPI Director, moved for<br>the recommendation for<br>approval of the proposed<br>splitting of the DEET, and<br>was duly seconded by<br>Prof. Maria Rizalia Teves,<br>CEBA Dean. |', '# PROPOSAL TO SPLIT THE EXISTING DEET INTO THREE (3) DISTINCT DEPARTMENTS IN THE COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\n\n#### BACKGROUND L.\n\nIn reference to the BOR Resolution No. 138 series 2017 -Approved Department Structures of the College of Engineering & Technology (COET), the Department of Electrical Engineering and Technology (DEET) is currently the largest department of the College of Engineering and Technology, housing six (6) undergraduate programs and with one graduate programs, which are as follows:\n\n#### Undergraduate programs a.', "#### Undergraduate programs a.\n\n- 1. BS Electronics Engineering (BSECE) 2 sections\n- 2. BET-Electronics Engineering Technology ( ESET) 1 ection\n- 3. BS Computer Engineering (BS CpE)- 1 sec. on\n- 4. BS Electrical Engineering (BS EE)-1 ection\n- 5. BET-Electrical Engineering Technolos, 3ET-ELL 1- 1 section\n- 6. BS Industrial Automation & Me ronic SIAM) 1 section\n- b. Graduate program-MS Electric Engineering (MS EE) with 2 tracks:\n\t- 1. MS EE in Power System ' ack ( + + + + EE program)\n\t- 2. MS EE in Microelectronics der the ECE program)\n\nAll these programs came to be rock of the DEET after the merging of the former College of Engineering and the School of ineering Technology. The idea then was to optimize access and utilization of resour es beth hun. and facilities in nature. Several years after said merger, operational difficultics >\n\nMoreover, the C = 1 a. with ts tract has an ongoing proposal for the creation of the following:", 'Moreover, the C = 1 a. with ts tract has an ongoing proposal for the creation of the following:\n\n- a. MS ECL nder the ECE program)\n- b. Mas boon Sobor. Joneering (Under EE with Collaboration with ME program)\n- c. PhD in Lectrical Engineering (PhD EE)\n\t- (PhD ECE)\n\nThis ture de elopment has to be prepared for in the creation of the departments.\n\n# THE HIS ST STI DENT POPULATION\n\nThe DEET has a total of 1,092 students as of 1st semester, SY. 2022-2023 for undergraduate programs and has 42 students in the graduate program, the highest so far compared to the other department within the College of Engineering & Technology - making the department as big as College of Computer Studies (CCS) and/or College of Economics and Business Administration (CEBA). The 200 biggest department in the College of Engineering is DMRET, which has only four (4) programs, and then the rest of the departments have only two (2) or three (3) programs.\n\n#### 11. RATIONALE:\n\n#### Significant Impact to Communities:', '#### 11. RATIONALE:\n\n#### Significant Impact to Communities:\n\nThe Department of Electrical Engineering and Technology can be considered to have significant impact at the National Level based on the following performance and achievements:', '- 1. The BSEE graduates consistently producing several 100 percent Board Exam Passers for Registered Electrical Engineers (REE) for the past five years. In fact, the program also produced several REE - PRC Board Exams Top placers (Top 1 to 10 Placers). In year 2021, MSU-IIT ranks 2nd Top Performing Schools in Electrical Engineering Licensure Examination in the country.\n- 2. The BSECE graduates also produce 90 to 100 percent PRC Board Exam Passers for Electronics Engineers for the past five years with some one to to 10 placers.\n- 3. Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering program is & CHF -COD Center of Development accreditation status.\n- 4. Bachelor of Science in Electronics Engineering pro ran. CHED-COE Center of Excellent accreditation status.\n- 5. Ongoing externally funded Projects worth ral m. "ion Pesos initiated by some Professors in BSECE, BSEE and BSCpE c also also that this department ended contributed to national develo ment.', 'The Department of Electrical Engin ering - - Ter nology can be considered to have significant impact also at International Le. achievements:\n\n- 1. The Faculty members a students from both programs in BSEE, BSCpE, BSIAM, BET-ELET, BET-SET MSEE produced several scientific papers which were presented in different National Conferences, and then eventually publishing them i . Scopus Index Journal Publications.\n- 2. The BSEE program on ther hand, currently establishing a Teaching Collaboration with MOA bewes TiM, alaysia.\n- 3. Several Fa lity mems in DEET also had undergone International Training in Solar Photo-volt. System I signs at Tatung University, Taipee, Taiwan.\n\n# Management in fficiency:', "# Management in fficiency:\n\nMar \\_ ... \\_ \\_ \\_ \\_ \\_ ty resulting in inefficiency is evident, which needs to be addressed to sustain the deparment's gains and continue to achieve its goals? The prevailing default concept at the Institute leve and even at the national level as perceived by DBM concerning the depar ment's size is to constitute only one or a couple of programs only per department. As such, the DE with n merous programs under him, is treated similarly with other departments in terms of in gement structure and support. This current treatment is acceptable to other departments with a couple of programs under it, but it meant less efficient coordination from planning down to execution of activities as in the case of DEET.", 'Sound management practice considers the span of the structure for efficient operations. Having seven distinct programs under the DEET overburdens the leadership; especially those numbers of program coordinators are limited as the Institute imposes a fixed number for every department - irrespective of the number of programs under it.\n\n#### The following are noteworthy to ponder upon:\n\na. Having two (2) sections for the BSE ECE program is just like having an additional program, treating the department with seven (7) programs in terms of faculty loading. Henceforth, a big challenge for a department chairman is to supervise the operation of each program efficiently.', '- b. The current department is headed by a department chairperson with mine (9) units de-loading with program coordinators for each program. The department chair having six (6) undergraduate programs cannot oversee/supervise efficiently the operation of each program to deliver the three mandates: Instruction, Research, and Extension.\n- c. Compared to the original department before the merger with the technology program, the old department only has three (3) undergraduate programs and one (1) graduate program. Henceforth, the efficiency is compromised compared to those departments having only 2-4 programs to manage.', "- d. The assigned department coordinators for the (1) Research & Extension, (2) SOJT, (3) Laboratory, (4 )Graduate program is not as efficient to manage, plan and coordinate for the seven (7) programs as compared to those departments that only have 2-4 programs. Further, coordinators cannot also relate adequately to all programs, e.g., for an ECE faculty assigned as SOJT coordinator, he/she won't have a network to electrical companies, where ECE and EE serve different == of indestries. This is the same with the Research and Extension and Laboratory coo.", '- e. one (1) dedicated department staff for six (6) undergraduate grams and one (1) graduate program is obviously inefficient, as compread incordepartments having only 2-4 programs. The assigned staff is expected \\* > be overwhelmed with the workload, particularly during enrollment ? ther side ultaneous activities of these six (6) programs. It is expected that there a co. mi e to data management, data filing of essential milestones of each rogram, and ordination to all faculty. Thus, catching up with the short notice a \\ deadlies deadline for needed reports and necessary submission of documents w a prev lent.', '- Heterogeneous program groups There are somehow three (3) unique and t. different types of industry p nevers u. r the existing department. The difference of the scope of work and in rest obvio sly observed. For example, the Electronics Engineering (ECE) are for to serve the industries related to electronics, communications ser ices. IC D and semiconductor companies, whereas, the Computer Enginer = (C) served the sector related to software design, firmware design, embedded sys , hardware design, and Artificial Intelligence (AI). On the other hand, F \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_ like power tility con nies, which ECE and CpE are not closely related to. It is the same with e BS IAN program.', 'like power tility con nies, which ECE and CpE are not closely related to. It is the same with e BS IAN program. Henceforth, not inter-related external affairs on coord ting ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------internation linkages.', '# II. ADVANT ES OF SPLITTING THE DEPARTMENT:\n\nEfficiency of Management - The difficulties owing to structural defects will be addressed e ev ting DEET organization structure will be split into three (3) new Departments with in the College of Engineering and Technology.\n\n### b. CHED and Washington Accord Accreditation:', '### b. CHED and Washington Accord Accreditation:\n\n- 1. With a smaller number of programs and inter-related program groupings, the department chairperson can efficiently address, oversee and supervise the operation of each program. The department chairperson, with the help of his/her coordinators: program, SOJT, research and extension, laboratory and graduate coordinator, can effectively, proficiently, competently, and closely monitored regularly all the aspects of maintaining and improving the performance indicator for CHED accreditation, and in preparation for international accreditation, such as Washington Accord.\n- 2. Knowing that the BS Electrical Engineering program is on a CHED-Center of Development status, so having this program and its closely interrelated BET-ELET program, be merged into one (1) separate department as DEET can be closely', 'monitored and supervised efficiently. Merging these two programs into one department only can be efficiently manage and closely monitored and easily be supervised by the department chairperson and his/her five coordinators regularly including all the aspects of improving the performance indicator for CHED accreditation and raising the program accreditation status from CHED COD to CHED-COE.', '3. Merging the two programs of BSECE and BET -ESET into one department as DECET will create the same scenario as stated above. Knowing that the BS ECE is a CHED-Center of Excellence, so having this program and its closely interrelated BET-ESET programs into one (1) separate department, can be managed efficiently by one department chairperson. Also, creating these two stated programs into one (1) department can be effectively, proficiently, competently, and closely monitored and easily be supervised by new department chairperson and his/her five (5) coordinators on a regular basis in all the aspects of maintaining and further improving the performance indicator for CHED accreditation, and in preparation for internati acceeditation, e.g., Washington Accord.\n\nMoreover, it is also true with the other two remain of the BSCpE and BSIAM to be merged into (1) separate de ments vith the same organizational structure to be created as proposed herei^', 'Moreover, it is also true with the other two remain of the BSCpE and BSIAM to be merged into (1) separate de ments vith the same organizational structure to be created as proposed herei^\n\n### III. THE PROPOSAL: SPLITTING OF DEET INTO THEE ( \\STING DEPARTMENTS\n\n#### A. Program Composition per Departm ..\n\nThe existing DEET is proposed to be di ided/sp it into three (3) distinct departments with programs under each assessed to n closer affinity to each other, namely:\n\n# Dept. of Electrical Engineering and Team and Te\n\n#### Undergradu> \\*\\* "rogra. " (EET):\n\n- 1. SS Elec. I Engineering (BS EE)-1 section.\n- 2. BET-Electr Il Engineering Technology (BET-ELET) 1 section.\n\n#### Grau ate picolam (DEET):\n\n- 1 EE (Power System track) existing.\n- 2. Ivis Robotics Engineering (Under Proposal Review)\n- 3 PhD EE (under proposal review).\n\n# Dept. of Electronics Engineering and Technology (DECET):\n\n# idergraduate programs (DECET):', '# Dept. of Electronics Engineering and Technology (DECET):\n\n# idergraduate programs (DECET):\n\n- 1. BS Electronics Engineering (BSECE) 2 sections.\n- 2. BET-Electronics Engineering Technology (BET-ESET) 1 section.\n\n# Graduate programs (DECET):\n\n- 1. MS EE (Microelectronics track) (existing to be replaced by MS ECE)\n- 2. MS ECE (under proposal review).\n- 3. PhD ECE (under proposal draft).\n- 2. Dept. of Computer Engineering and Mechatronics (DCEM): Undergraduate programs:\n\n# 1. BS Computer Engineering (BSCpE) - 1 section.\n\n2. BS Industrial Automation & Mechatronics (BSIAM) - 1 section\n\nCommon facilities are to be shared by the programs involved, while distinct facilities to a program shall be under the supervision of said program. Staff and faculty support, consequent to the splitting, shall be afforded separately to the split departments, as governed by existing institute and university policies.', 'Presented in Figure 1 are the proposed organizational structures split into three (3) distinct departments which is based on the existing BOR Resolution No. 138 series 2017=Approved Department Structures of the College of Engineering & Technology (COET).\n\nFigure 1. Proposed organizational seructu split into three (3) distinct departments.\n\n#### ll. Department Structure/Description\n\nApplying the ex ting dep ment structure as per BOR Resolution No. 138 series 2017-Approved Department tructures f the College of Engineering & Technology (COET), each Department shall be head hairperson with the same conventional and existing functions. Addressing the broade. and voluminous task of the Department Chairperson, a department staff, program coor ate and OJT coordinator are retained.\n\n# i. Fogram inordinators', "# i. Fogram inordinators\n\nCOE& . 'epartments are each composed of several programs. Relying supervision of all 'hese pr grams solely to the chairperson, who is fairly expected to be thoroughly Co. ant with one program only, would be tedious and very complicated. A coordinator for each program offering to assist the chairperson is therefore necessary to ensure smooth operations.\n\n# ii. Graduate Program Coordinator\n\nEach department with a graduate program offering shall be provided a graduate program coordinator. Concerns and challenges in the graduate programs are peculiar from those in the undergraduate. The coordinator shall assist the department chairperson in all matters affecting their respective graduate program offering.\n\n# iii. SOJT Coordinator", '# iii. SOJT Coordinator\n\nPlacement of every student for a well supervised On-the-Job Training requires a lot of time, planning, coordination and follow-ups. OJT is a very crucial preparation for every student considering their soon joining the work industry. A coordinator is needed for this special need.\n\n#### iv. Research and Extension Coordinator\n\nInstitutionalized and sustained research and extension programs at the department require a designated faculty to focus, plan and coordinate activities on the matter.\n\n#### v. Laboratory Coordinator\n\nEach department laboratories shall operate giving access to all programs needed and suited for it. Consequently, coordination then becomes essential. In addition, the coordinator that all laboratories are periodically inventoried, maintained, consumables replenished on time, and calibration properly done.\n\n#### vi. Office Staff', '#### vi. Office Staff\n\nEach department shall be provided with an Office Staff. The staff shall assist the department in the preparation, processing, and following-up of the department interoffice transactions, encoding of reports, accreditation de cument preparations, and procurement matters, among others.', '| Position     | Department                                                        | Existi<br>Numb.<br>Personne | Personi Assigned             |\n|--------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------|------------------------------|\n| Office Staff | Department of Electrical<br>Engineering and Technology<br>(DEET)  |                             | Jabile, Susana G<br>(casual) |\n| Office staff | Department of Electronics<br>Engineering and Technolog<br>(DECET) | Non                         | Need to Hire.<br>(unfilled)  |\n| Office Staff | Department of Com<br>Engineering and<br>Mechatronics CEM          | None                        | Need to Hire.<br>(unfilled)  |\n\n#### vii. Laboratory Tech.', '#### vii. Laboratory Tech.\n\nThere shall b to aboratory technician for each program offering. This technician hall hand mandated laboratories for the program offerings. On the other hand, ansient la oratories consequent to ongoing research shall be hired and funder by the research project.', '| Departmont                                              | Program  | Existing<br>Number<br>Technician                            | Personnel Assigned                       |\n|---------------------------------------------------------|----------|-------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|\n| Electri<br>E) gineering<br>and<br>Technolog<br>(DEET)   | BSEE     | 1                                                           | Elmer Go-oc<br>(Permanent)               |\n|                                                         | BET-FLET | 1                                                           | Salado, Joe Mark E.<br>(casual)          |\n| Electronics<br>Engineering<br>and<br>Technology (DECET) | BSECE    | 1                                                           | Uy, U-Lee Ariel C. (job<br>order/casual) |', '| Electronics<br>Engineering<br>and<br>Technology (DECET) | BSECE    | 1                                                           | Uy, U-Lee Ariel C. (job<br>order/casual) |\n|                                                         | BET-ESET | None                                                        | Need to Hire.<br>(unfilled)              |\n| Computer<br>Engineering<br>and<br>Mechatronics (DCEM)   | BSCpE    | None<br>* also to<br>handle ES<br>computing<br>laboratories | Need to hire<br>(Unfilled)               |\n|                                                         | BSIAM    | None                                                        | Need to Hire.<br>(unfilled)              |', '# IV. FACULTY DELOADING AND STAFF/TECHNICIAN HIRING REQUIREMENTS:\n\nExisting policies for equivalent teaching load considerations shall be observed. Below are the existing faculty deloading of the following:\n\n- · Department Chairperson 9 units\n- · Department Graduate Coordinator 3 units\n- · Department Program Coordinators:\n\t- o BSEE / BET-ELET 3 units\n\t- o BSECE / BET-ESET 3 units\n\t- o BSCpE / BSIAM 3 units\n- · Department SOJT Coordinator 3 units\n- · Department Research and Extension Coordinator · · units\n- · Department Laboratory Coordinator 3 units', 'Moreover, in order to manage and supervise efficiently "ne . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . for each program in terms of regular procurement of laborat / supplies, maintenance and repair/calibration of test equipment and inventory, a mus to have one (1) dedicated laboratory technician for each undergraduate program On t. ther nand, each department shall have one (1) office staff in the preparation, proces ng, and follow ng-up of the department interoffice transactions, encoding of reports, accredit: on docum. It preparations, and procurement matters, among others. Below are the position to . Silled from the current set-up:\n\n- A. Hiring of Laboratory Technic s for & following programs:\n\t- 1. BET-ESET\n\t- 2. BSCpE\n\t- 3. BSIAM\n- B. Hiring of Office Staff to be following departments:\n\t- 1. DECET\n\t- 2. DCEM', '- A. Hiring of Laboratory Technic s for & following programs:\n\t- 1. BET-ESET\n\t- 2. BSCpE\n\t- 3. BSIAM\n- B. Hiring of Office Staff to be following departments:\n\t- 1. DECET\n\t- 2. DCEM\n\nThis proposal is l to the strengthening of the affected programs as we are definitely facing new challeng now ... in the future. Sound management organizational structure is indispensable \\* ontimiz the operation efficiently at the department level. This could be a beneficial chan \'s Tor aujustinent and innovation that we cannot ignore.\n\nThis roposa lad been thoroughly discussed and deliberated accordingly and was unani Tously con "urred by Faculty and Staff of the existing Department of Electrical Engineering and \\ >ology \\ the College of Engineering and Technology in MSU-Iligan Institute of technology\n\nPROPONENT:\n\nDr. RENNE E-MICULOB, MBA, D.ENG Chairperson, DEET\n\n# CONCURRED BY:', 'BSECE & BET-ESET FACULTY BSCpE FACULTY BSEE/BET-ELET FACULTY Name & Signature Name & Signature Name & Signature C offerson A. Hora', 'Assoc. Prof. V Prof. Earl Ryan M. Aleluya Dr Rennie E. Miculob Asst. Prof. IV Assoc. Prof. V A Lambir Prof. Mercedenia Lambino Dr. Cherry Mae G. Villame -AR. Estoperez Assoc, Prof. V Asst. Prof. IV Prof. VI Prof. Angline L. Teatro rnel D. Zama Dr. Carl John Ol Salaan Assoc. Prof. III st. Pro V Prof. III 00 Dr. Olga Joy L. Gerasta Er gr. Stephen laim Dr. Marven E. Jabian Prof. VI In actor II Assoc. Prof. III Harreez V. Quimque Engr. F Incis Janna. Alagon Prof. Anacita P. Tahud Assoc. Prof. V Instructor - III Assoc. Prof. V Prof. Jennibeth Gatal Engr. Stephanie R. Visitacion Prof. Karl Martin A. Aldueso Asst Prof. IV (For BOR) Asst. Prof. IV ONAV BSIAM FACULTY Prof. Nieva M. Mapula Name & Signature Engr. Abdul Aziz G. Mabaning Assoc. Prof. V (For BOR) Prof. Santiago R. Evasco Jr. Dr. Moheddin U. Sumagi van (For Bord) Professor III Dr. G Prof. Erman 5. Marajas ene Fe P. Palencia Engr. Rovick P. Tarife (For BOR) Professor III Instructor III', 'coe.dean@g.msuiit.edu.ph\n\nwww.msuiit.edu.ph\n\nInfluencing the Future\n\n# PROPOSAL TO SPLIT THE EXISTING DEET INTO THREE (3) DISTINCT DEPARTMENTS IN THE COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\n\n#### BACKGROUND 1.\n\nIn reference to the BOR Resolution No. 138 series 2017 -Approved Department Structures of the College of Engineering & Technology (COET), the Department of Electrical Engineering and Technology (DEET) is currently the largest department of the College of Engineering and Technology, housing six (6) undergraduate programs and with one graduate programs, which are as follows:\n\n#### Undergraduate programs a.', '#### Undergraduate programs a.\n\n- 1. BS Electronics Engineering (BSECE) 2 sections\n- 2. BET-Electronics Engineering Technology (FE ESET) 1 ection\n- 3. BS Computer Engineering (BS CpE)- 1 secu on\n- 4. BS Electrical Engineering (BS EE)-1 section\n- 5. BET-Electrical Engineering Techno! 5, 7ET-ELL 1 1 section\n- 6. BS Industrial Automation & Mechonic 1 section\n- b. Graduate program-MS Electrica Engineerin (MS EE) with 2 tracks:\n\t- 1. MS EE in Power System + ack (u = +h EE program)\n\t- 2. MS EE in Microelectronics der the ECE program)\n\nAll these programs came to be roo of the DEET after the merging of the former College of Engineering and the Sch ol or ineering Technology. The idea then was to optimize access and utilization of resources beth hun and facilities in nature. Several years after said merger, operational difficultie & in , erent restrictions are felt in the management of the DEET.\n\nMoreover, the D . c . a . with is tract has an ongoing proposal for the creation of the following:', 'Moreover, the D . c . a . with is tract has an ongoing proposal for the creation of the following:\n\n- a. MSECE der the CE program)\n- b. No. both Juneering (Under EE with Collaboration with ME program)\n- c. PhD in E. trical Engineering (PhD EE)\n\t- onics Engineering (PhD ECE)\n\nThis to re de lopment has to be prepared for in the creation of the departments.\n\n# THE HIG ST STU ENT POPULATION\n\nThe DEET has a total of 1,092 students as of 1st semester, SY. 2022-2023 for undergraduate programs and has 42 students in the graduate program, the highest so far compared to the other department within the College of Engineering & Technology - making the department as big as College of Computer Studies (CCS) and/or College of Economics and Business Administration (CEBA). The 2nd biggest department in the College of Engineering is DMRET, which has only four (4) programs, and then the rest of the departments have only two (2) or three (3) programs.\n\n#### RATIONALE: 11.', '#### RATIONALE: 11.\n\n# Significant Impact to Communities:\n\nThe Department of Electrical Engineering and Technology can be considered to have significant impact at the National Level based on the following performance and achievements:', '- 1. The BSEE graduates consistently producing several 100 percent Board Exam Passers for Registered Electrical Engineers (REE) for the past five years. In fact, the program also produced several REE - PRC Board Exams Top placers (Top 1 to 10 Placers). In year 2021, MSU-IIT ranks 2nd Top Performing Schools in Electrical Engineering Licensure Examination in the country.\n- 2. The BSECE graduates also produce 90 to 100 percent PRC Board Exam Passers for Electronics Engineers for the past five years with some one to to 10 placers.\n- 3. Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering program is o. CHE -COD Center of Development accreditation status.\n- 4. Bachelor of Science in Electronics Engineering pro ram, CHED-COE Center of Excellent accreditation status.\n- 5. Ongoing externally funded Projects worth ral million Pesos initiated by some Professors in BSECE, BSEE and BSCpE calso also a the fact that this department ended contributed to national development.', 'The Department of Electrical Engine in Ter" nology can be considered to have significant impact also at International Lev based on the following performance and or achievements:\n\n- 1. The Faculty members ar stud ts from both programs in BSEE, BSCpE, BSIAM, BET-ELET, BET-FSET & MSEE produced several scientific papers which were presented in different National Conferences, and then eventually publishing them in Scopus Index Journal Publications.\n- 2. The BSEE program on ther hand, currently establishing a Teaching Collaboration with MOA be wee TiM, I dlaysia.\n- 3. Several Fac Ity memb s in DEET also had undergone International Training in Solar Photo-volta System D signs at Tatung University, Taipee, Taiwan.\n\n# Management In "ficiency:', '# Management In "ficiency:\n\nMan- y resulting in inefficiency is evident, which needs to be addressed to sustain the depart ent\'s gains and continue to achieve its goals? The prevailing default concept at the Institu > leven at the national level as perceived by DBM concerning the depar ment\'s size is to constitute only one or a couple of programs only per department. As such, the DE vith ni nerous programs under him, is treated similarly with other departments in terms of ment structure and support. This current treatment is acceptable to other departments with a couple of programs under it, but it meant less efficient coordination from planning down to execution of activities as in the case of DEET.', 'Sound management practice considers the span of the structure for efficient operations. Having seven distinct programs under the DEET overburdens the leadership; especially those numbers of program coordinators are limited as the Institute imposes a fixed number for every department - irrespective of the number of programs under it.\n\n# The following are noteworthy to ponder upon:\n\na. Having two (2) sections for the BSE ECE program is just like having an additional program, treating the department with seven (7) programs in terms of faculty loading. Henceforth, a big challenge for a department chairman is to supervise the operation of each program efficiently.', '- b. The current department is headed by a department chairperson with mine (9) units de-loading with program coordinators for each program. The department chair having six (6) undergraduate programs cannot oversee/supervise efficiently the operation of each program to deliver the three mandates: Instruction, Research, and Extension.\n- c. Compared to the original department before the merger with the technology program, the old department only has three (3) undergraduate programs and one (1) graduate program. Henceforth, the efficiency is compromised compared to those departments having only 2-4 programs to manage.', "- d. The assigned department coordinators for the (1) Research & Extension, (2) SOJT, (3) Laboratory, (4 )Graduate program is not as efficient to manage, plan and coordinate for the seven (7) programs as compared to those departments that only have 2-4 programs. Further, coordinators cannot also relate adequately to all programs, e.g., for an ECE faculty assigned as SOJT coordinator, he/she won't have a network to electrical companies, where ECE and EE serve different ones of ind stries. This is the same with the Research and Extension and Laboratory coo.", '- e. one (1) dedicated department staff for six (6) undergraduate grams and one (1) graduate program is obviously inefficient, as comp read in a departments having only 2-4 programs. The assigned staff is expected of be overwhelmed with the workload, particularly during enrollment ? ther si. ultaneous activities of these six (6) programs. It is expected that there is a comice to data management, data filing of essential milestones of each rogram, and ordination to all faculty. Thus, catching up with the short notice a | deadline for needed reports and necessary submission of documents we prev lient.', '- Heterogeneous program groups There are somehow three (3) unique and f. 3 different types of industry r ners u. " the existing department. The difference of the scope of work and in rest obvio sly observed. For example, the Electronics Engineering (ECE) are for t to serve the industries related to electronics, communications ser ices. IC D and semiconductor companies, whereas, the Computer Engine == (C) served the sector related to software design, firmware design, embedded sys . . s, hardware design, and Artificial Intelligence (AI). On the other hand, F . . . Engly ering (EE) is serving a different type of industry partner, like power tillity con nies, which ECE and CpE are not closely related to. It is the same with e BS IAN program. Henceforth, not inter-related external affairs on coord ting - - - engthening relationships with corporations, industries, and internation. I linkages.', '## II. ADVANT ES OF RE SPLITTING THE DEPARTMENT:\n\nEfficiency of Management - The difficulties owing to structural defects will be addressed a ex ting DEET organization structure will be split into three (3) new Departments within the College of Engineering and Technology.\n\n#### b. CHED and Washington Accord Accreditation:', '#### b. CHED and Washington Accord Accreditation:\n\n- 1. With a smaller number of programs and inter-related program groupings, the department chairperson can efficiently address, oversee and supervise the operation of each program. The department chairperson, with the help of his/her coordinators: program, SOJT, research and extension, laboratory and graduate coordinator, can effectively, proficiently, competently, and closely monitored regularly all the aspects of maintaining and improving the performance indicator for CHED accreditation, and in preparation for international accreditation, such as Washington Accord.\n- 2. Knowing that the BS Electrical Engineering program is on a CHED-Center of Development status, so having this program and its closely interrelated BET-ELET program, be merged into one (1) separate department as DEET can be closely', 'monitored and supervised efficiently. Merging these two programs in one department only can be efficiently manage and closely monitored and easily be supervised by the department chairperson and his/her five coordinators regularly including all the aspects of improving the performance indicator for CHED accreditation and raising the program accreditation status from CHED COD to CHED-COF.', "3. Merging the two programs of BSECE and BET -ESET into one department as DECET will create the same scenario as stated above. Knowing that the BS ECE is a CHED-Center of Excellence, so having this program and its closely interrelated BET-ESET programs into one (1) separate department, can be managed efficiently by one department chairperson. Also, creating these two stated programs into one (1) department can be effectively, proficiently, competently, and closely monitored and easily be supervised by new department chairperson and his/her five (5) coordinators on a regular basis in all the aspects of maintaining and further improving the nerformance indicator for CHED accreditation, and in preparation for internati | accreditation, e.g., Washington Accord.\n\nMoreover, it is also true with the other two remain of the BSCpE and BSIAM to be merged into (1) separate de ments vith the same organizational structure to be created as proposed here'", 'Moreover, it is also true with the other two remain of the BSCpE and BSIAM to be merged into (1) separate de ments vith the same organizational structure to be created as proposed here\'\n\n# III. THE PROPOSAL: SPLITTING OF DEET INTO TH\' EE ( \\STING DEPARTMENTS\n\n# A. Program Composition per Department\n\nThe existing DEET is proposed tr be dr ided/sr it into three (3) distinct departments with programs under each assessed to . closer affinity to each other, namely:\n\n# Dept. of Electrical Engineering and Team onlor DEET):\n\n# Undergradu> \\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\*\\* (")EET):\n\n- 1. SS Elec. I Engineering (BS EE)-1 section.\n- 3ET-Electral Engineering Technology (BET-ELET) 1 section.\n\n# Grau ate problam (DEET):\n\n- 1 EE (Power System track) existing.\n- 2. Ivis Robotics Engineering (Under Proposal Review)\n- 3. PhD EE (under proposal review).\n\n# Dept. of Electronics Engineering and Technology (DECET):\n\n# ndergraduate programs (DECET):', '# Dept. of Electronics Engineering and Technology (DECET):\n\n# ndergraduate programs (DECET):\n\n- 1. BS Electronics Engineering (BSECE) 2 sections.\n- 2. BET-Electronics Engineering Technology (BET-ESET) 1 section.\n\n# Graduate programs (DECET):\n\n- 1. MS EE (Microelectronics track) (existing to be replaced by MS ECE)\n- 2. MS ECE (under proposal review).\n- 3. PhD ECE (under proposal draft).\n\n# 2. Dept. of Computer Engineering and Mechatronics (DCEM):\n\n# Undergraduate programs:\n\n- 1. BS Computer Engineering (BSCpE) 1 section.\n- 2. BS Industrial Automation & Mechatronics (BSIAM) 1 section\n\nCommon facilities are to be shared by the programs involved, while distinct facilities to a program shall be under the supervision of said program. Staff and faculty support, consequent to the splitting, shall be afforded separately to the split departments, as governed by existing institute and university policies.', 'Presented in Figure 1 are the proposed organizational structures split into three (3) distinct departments which is based on the existing BOR Resolution No. 138 series 2017=Approved Department Structures of the College of Engineering & Technology (COET).\n\nFigure 1. Proposed organizational Cructs split into three (3) distinct departments.\n\n#### Department Structure/Descrintion ll.\n\nApplying the e sting de thent structure as per BOR Resolution No. 138 series 2017-Approved Department tructures of the College of Engineering & Technology (COET), each Department shall / head nairperson with the same conventional and existing functions. Addressing the broade and voluminous task of the Department Chairperson, a department staff, ate and OJT coordinator are retained. program coo\n\n# ാgram inordinators', '# ാgram inordinators\n\nCOE& . Jepartments are each composed of several programs. Relying supervision of all \\*hese p bgrams solely to the chairperson, who is fairly expected to be thoroughly sant with one program only, would be tedious and very complicated. A 6 coordinator for each program offering to assist the chairperson is therefore necessary to ensure smooth operations.\n\n# ii. Graduate Program Coordinator\n\nEach department with a graduate program offering shall be provided a graduate program coordinator. Concerns and challenges in the graduate programs are peculiar from those in the undergraduate. The coordinator shall assist the department chairperson in all matters affecting their respective graduate program offering.\n\n# iii. SOJT Coordinator', '# iii. SOJT Coordinator\n\nPlacement of every student for a well supervised On-the-Job Training requires a lot of time, planning, coordination and follow-ups. OJT is a very crucial preparation for every student considering their soon joining the work industry. A coordinator is needed for this special need.\n\n### iv. Research and Extension Coordinator\n\nInstitutionalized and sustained research and extension programs at the department require a designated faculty to focus, plan and coordinate activities on the matter.\n\n#### v. Laboratory Coordinator\n\nEach department laboratories shall operate giving access to all programs needed and suited for it. Consequently, coordination then becomes essential. In addition, the coordinator that all laboratories are periodically inventoried, maintained, consumables replenished on time, and calibration properly done.\n\n#### vi. Office Staff', '#### vi. Office Staff\n\nEach department shall be provided with an Office Staff. The staff shall assist the department in the preparation, processing, and following-up of the department interoffice transactions, encoding of reports, accreditation d cument preparations, and procurement matters, among others.', '| Position     | Department                                                       | Existi<br>Numb<br>Personne | Person: Assigned             |\n|--------------|------------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------|------------------------------|\n| Office Staff | Department of Electrical<br>Engineering and Technology<br>(DEET) |                            | Jabile, Susana G<br>(casual) |\n| Office staff | Department of Electronics<br>Engineering and Technolo<br>(DECET) | Not                        | Need to Hire.<br>(unfilled)  |\n| Office Staff | Department of Corp.<br>Engineering and<br>Mechatronics / CEMA    | None                       | Need to Hire.<br>(unfilled)  |\n\n#### vii. Laboratory Techane', '#### vii. Laboratory Techane\n\nThere shall h st on aboratory technician for each program offering. This technician hall hand mandated laboratories for the program offerings. On the other hand ransient li >oratories consequent to ongoing research shall be hired and funde by th - - ne cive research project.', '| Department                                              | Program  | Existing<br>Number<br>Technician                            | Personnel Assigned                       |\n|---------------------------------------------------------|----------|-------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------|\n| Electrical<br>a gineering<br>and<br>Technolog (DEET)    | BSEE     | 1                                                           | Elmer Go-oc<br>(Permanent)               |\n|                                                         | BET-ELET | 1                                                           | Salado, Joe Mark E.<br>(casual)          |\n| Electronics<br>Engineering<br>and<br>Technology (DECET) | BSECE    | 1                                                           | Uy, U-Lee Ariel C. (job<br>order/casual) |', '| Electronics<br>Engineering<br>and<br>Technology (DECET) | BSECE    | 1                                                           | Uy, U-Lee Ariel C. (job<br>order/casual) |\n|                                                         | BET-ESET | None                                                        | Need to Hire.<br>(unfilled)              |\n| Computer<br>Engineering<br>and<br>Mechatronics (DCEM)   | BSCpE    | None<br>* also to<br>handle ES<br>computing<br>laboratories | Need to hire<br>(Unfilled)               |\n|                                                         | BSIAM    | None                                                        | Need to Hire.<br>(unfilled)              |', '### IV. FACULTY DELOADING AND STAFF/TECHNICIAN HIRING REQUIREMENTS:\n\nExisting policies for equivalent teaching load considerations shall be observed. Below are the existing faculty deloading of the following:\n\n- Department Chairperson 9 units\n- · Department Graduate Coordinator 3 units\n- · Department Program Coordinators:\n\t- o BSEE / BET-ELET 3 units\n\t- o BSECE / BET-ESET 3 units\n\t- o BSCpE / BSIAM 3 units\n- · Department SOJT Coordinator 3 units\n- · Department Research and Extension Coordinator · · units\n- · Department Laboratory Coordinator 3 units', 'Moreover, in order to manage and supervise efficiently for each program in terms of regular procurement of laborat / supplies, maintenance and repair/calibration of test equipment and inventory, a mus to have one (1) dedicated laboratory technician for each undergraduate program On t. ther hand, each department shall have one (1) office staff in the preparation, proces ng, and following-up of the department interoffice transactions, encoding of reports, accredit: on docum matters, among others. Below are the position to . "Illed from the current set-up:\n\n- A. Hiring of Laboratory Technic for for & following programs:\n\t- 1. BFT-FSFT\n\t- 2. BSCpE\n\t- 3. BSIAM\n- B. Hiring of Office Staff to following departments:\n\t- 1. DECET\n\t- 2. DCEM', "- A. Hiring of Laboratory Technic for for & following programs:\n\t- 1. BFT-FSFT\n\t- 2. BSCpE\n\t- 3. BSIAM\n- B. Hiring of Office Staff to following departments:\n\t- 1. DECET\n\t- 2. DCEM\n\nThis proposal is l to the strengthening of the affected programs as we are definitely facing new challeng now .... in the future. Sound management organizational structure is indispensable \\*^ ontimiz the operation efficiently at the department level. This could be a beneficial chan 's ror aujust nent and innovation that we cannot ignore.\n\nThis roposa lad been thoroughly discussed and deliberated accordingly and was unani lously con urred by Faculty and Staff of the existing Department of Electrical Engineering and \\ >ology \\ the College of Engineering and Technology in MSU-Iligan Institute of technology\n\nPROPONENT:\n\nDr. RENNIE E. MICULOB, MBA, D.ENG Chairperson, DEET\n\nCONCURRED BY:", "BSECE & BET-ESET FACULTY BSCpE FACULTY BSEE/BET-ELET FACULTY Name & Signature Name & Signature Name & Signature Br Sefferson A. Hora Prof. Earl Ryan M. Alghuya Dr. Rennie E. Miculob Assoc Prof. V Asst. Porof. IV Assoc. Prof. V Prof. Mercedenia Lambino Dr. Eherry Mae G. Villame A. Estoperez Assoc. Prof. V Asst. Prof. IV Prof. VI Prof. Angline L. Teatro Dr. Carl John O. Salaan Arnel D. Zama Assoc. Prof. III Asst. Pro 'V Prof. III Dr. Olga Joy L. Gerasta Er fr. Stephen laim Dr. Marven E. Jabian Prof. VI In actor II Assoc. Prof. III Engr. Francis Jana A. Alagon Dr. Harreez V. Quimque Prof. Anacita P. Tahud Assoc. Prof. V Instructor - III Assoc. Prof. V AAA Prof. Jennibeth Gatal Engr. Stephanie R. Visitacion Prof. Karl Martin A. Aldueso Asst Prof. IV (For BOR) Asst. Prof. IV 1700 BSIAM FACULTY Prof. Nieva M Mapula Name & Signature Engr. Abdul Aziz G. Mabaning Assoc. Prof. V (For BOR) LIDE Prof. Santiago R. Evasco Jr. Dr. Moheddin U. Sumagay Professor III For BOR) 1000 Dr. Gene Fe P.", 'Prof. Nieva M Mapula Name & Signature Engr. Abdul Aziz G. Mabaning Assoc. Prof. V (For BOR) LIDE Prof. Santiago R. Evasco Jr. Dr. Moheddin U. Sumagay Professor III For BOR) 1000 Dr. Gene Fe P. Palencia Prof. Erman S. Marajas Engr. Rovick P. Tarife (For BOR) Arofessor III Instructor III coe.dean@g.msuiit.edu.ph Influencing the Future www.msuiit.edu.ph']
